00:10:46.340 --> 00:10:50.610
in a much more simplified way
so that you can understand,

00:10:50.610 --> 00:10:54.900
when we speak of accessibility
testing, how we're approaching it.

00:10:54.900 --> 00:10:58.740
This is the reason that I
always add this map here

00:10:58.740 --> 00:11:04.930
because I think it's a much more
effective way to explain to somebody

00:11:04.930 --> 00:11:09.740
who may not know what accessibility
is and what are the guidelines,

00:11:09.740 --> 00:11:13.050
or where to even begin
with accessibility testing.

00:11:13.050 --> 00:11:15.440
I think this breaks
it down very nicely.

00:11:15.440 --> 00:11:20.800
I continue, when I present to
people that don't necessarily know

00:11:20.800 --> 00:11:23.233
what the WCAG is,
and I might be assuming

00:11:23.234 --> 00:11:24.970
that everyone here does know,

00:11:25.451 --> 00:11:28.440
I break it down
according to the map.

00:11:28.440 --> 00:11:33.610
We have the four principles of
the WCAG, and within the four-

00:11:33.610 --> 00:11:37.790
the four principles are allocated
into three conformance levels.

00:11:37.790 --> 00:11:45.070
Oftentimes, I hear, "My
organization needs WCAG AA and 2.1.

00:11:45.070 --> 00:11:52.310
Is that what you cover?" I emphasize
that if you're looking for AA,

00:11:52.310 --> 00:11:56.070
which we all know is
more or less the standard

00:11:56.070 --> 00:12:01.720
or that average recommendation to
make sure that you're conforming to,

00:12:02.810 --> 00:12:06.730
then one must understand that
you have to cover level A,

00:12:06.730 --> 00:12:11.960
which is our critical criteria,
and the AA in order to say

00:12:11.960 --> 00:12:16.220
that you're conforming
to AA guidelines.

00:12:17.440 --> 00:12:20.280
AAA, as we know and I'm
sure that we've heard it

00:12:20.280 --> 00:12:23.570
in the last two days,
is much more strict.

00:12:23.570 --> 00:12:26.000
Generally, we're talking
about federal government

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:28.480
and federally funded organizations.

00:12:28.480 --> 00:12:31.230
It's the highest
level of conformance.

00:12:31.230 --> 00:12:35.480
I would hope that that's where we're
going to reach in the near future,

00:12:35.480 --> 00:12:38.330
but I also understand,
and you'll see it later on,

00:12:38.330 --> 00:12:41.130
that accessibility tends to
be something that not a lot

00:12:41.130 --> 00:12:46.190
of people understand and they
have the motivation to do so.

00:12:46.190 --> 00:12:49.410
Therefore,
we need to find a happy medium.

00:12:49.410 --> 00:12:54.940
What can we require that
will remove barriers,

00:12:54.940 --> 00:12:59.540
but also allow companies,
organizations, product owners,

00:12:59.540 --> 00:13:05.960
website owners to continue building
without having to constantly worry

00:13:05.960 --> 00:13:09.090
that they're not meeting the
highest level of conformance?

00:13:09.090 --> 00:13:10.220
That's the way that I view it.

00:13:11.350 --> 00:13:13.960
Of course, I break this down
into the success criteria so

00:13:13.960 --> 00:13:17.060
that we can understand that
if you have to cover A and AA,

00:13:17.060 --> 00:13:19.830
then you're actually
covering 50 success criteria.

00:13:19.830 --> 00:13:24.910
I'm always asked the question,
how much do you cover?

00:13:24.910 --> 00:13:30.530
We, of course, are in the test
automation space, and the percent

00:13:30.530 --> 00:13:33.120
of coverage is something
that worries everybody

00:13:33.120 --> 00:13:36.900
because if you don't cover
100%, then it's useless.

00:13:36.900 --> 00:13:38.660
Well, I don't believe that.

00:13:38.660 --> 00:13:42.470
I believe that what we need
to find is a way to test

00:13:42.470 --> 00:13:48.280
and assess for accessibility
that will allow the professionals

00:13:48.280 --> 00:13:52.260
in our space to do
the work of an expert.

00:13:52.260 --> 00:13:55.070
Which is what we call them,
subject-matter experts.

00:13:55.070 --> 00:13:59.520
My team, we have subject-matter
experts, and I see the complexity

00:13:59.520 --> 00:14:05.040
of what- the complex issues
that we can solve versus issues

00:14:05.040 --> 00:14:09.310
that may be able to be solved
by test automation, not

00:14:09.310 --> 00:14:13.330
to cover this 100%,
rather to be able to say,

00:14:13.330 --> 00:14:15.420
"Okay, we have 50 success criteria.

00:14:15.420 --> 00:14:17.880
We know that one of
them needs 10 tests.

00:14:17.880 --> 00:14:23.240
Those 10 tests were covered while
we were still in pre-production."

00:14:23.240 --> 00:14:24.620
I hope I haven't lost anyone yet.

