we have to have it in place,

00:14:57.080 --> 00:15:02.050
but it's kind of that world
that we don't really understand.

00:15:02.050 --> 00:15:06.060
I feel accessibility tends to
be that way for a lot of people

00:15:07.310 --> 00:15:12.770
in the product teams,
if it's product or developers,

00:15:12.770 --> 00:15:17.340
sometimes designers as well
and the QA, quality assurance.

00:15:17.340 --> 00:15:21.960
I feel this space tends
to be a black box to them.

00:15:21.960 --> 00:15:24.320
It's one of the reasons,
or at least this is what I like

00:15:24.320 --> 00:15:30.130
to believe in the way that I'm
leading this, that they want

00:15:30.130 --> 00:15:32.300
to implement accessibility,
but they don't really know

00:15:32.300 --> 00:15:36.360
how to because it's left in the
hands of professionals and experts.

00:15:37.670 --> 00:15:41.170
I do feel accessibility
tends to be convoluted.

00:15:41.170 --> 00:15:42.290
It's complex.

00:15:42.290 --> 00:15:48.540
Not a lot of people understand
what really needs to be done,

00:15:48.540 --> 00:15:51.280
and they have the
motivation to do so.

00:15:51.280 --> 00:15:56.690
My suggestion is always to
start at the beginning, and try

00:15:56.690 --> 00:15:59.640
to implement some sort of
standard operating procedure

00:15:59.640 --> 00:16:04.810
within an organization that will
allude to how a product needs

00:16:04.810 --> 00:16:09.140
to be tested, assessed and
monitored for accessibility.

00:16:10.560 --> 00:16:14.640
This is really the beginning,
the baby steps for testing,

00:16:14.640 --> 00:16:15.460
at the end of the day.

00:16:15.460 --> 00:16:20.780
Because I can offer an
organization a tool and tell them,

00:16:20.780 --> 00:16:24.230
"Use this and cover your
accessibility grounds,"

00:16:24.230 --> 00:16:30.840
but that's not really where my
tool is going to be most effective.

00:16:30.840 --> 00:16:35.430
My tool or my product is
going to be most effective

00:16:35.430 --> 00:16:39.890
for an organization that has
already implemented the idea

00:16:39.890 --> 00:16:42.380
of accessibility across the board.

00:16:42.380 --> 00:16:47.060
Meaning, the design and
development team understand

00:16:47.060 --> 00:16:49.760
and have some sort of
training in place or a program

00:16:49.760 --> 00:16:51.740
in place for accessibility.

00:16:51.740 --> 00:16:56.250
Some sort of a guideline,
not the WCAG, internal policy

00:16:56.250 --> 00:16:58.660
for what is the expectation.

00:16:58.660 --> 00:17:03.400
The business stakeholders within
the company have buy-in also

00:17:03.400 --> 00:17:05.920
to these either standard
operating procedures

00:17:05.920 --> 00:17:08.420
or the accessibility programs.

00:17:08.420 --> 00:17:14.970
Only then do I believe that
a testing tool can assist

00:17:14.970 --> 00:17:17.260
and can support the efforts
of the organization.

00:17:18.380 --> 00:17:22.320
I always turn to-- I call it the
standard operating procedure.

00:17:22.320 --> 00:17:25.890
We can call it guidelines,
we can call it standards

00:17:25.890 --> 00:17:32.400
or internal company
policies for accessibility.

00:17:32.400 --> 00:17:37.010
Then accessibility
testing can be implemented

00:17:37.010 --> 00:17:39.530
and the accessibility
can be monitored.

00:17:39.530 --> 00:17:45.430
When I speak of organizations or
products, I'm referring primarily

00:17:45.430 --> 00:17:47.540
to web applications.

00:17:47.540 --> 00:17:53.520
In the world of websites,
because we are in WordPress Day,

00:17:53.520 --> 00:17:55.830
the websites that I
would be referring

00:17:55.830 --> 00:17:58.990
to are more complex e-commerce
sites, sites that have a lot

00:17:58.990 --> 00:18:00.540
of functionality in them.

00:18:00.540 --> 00:18:04.290
That's where I come from
when I'm viewing or speaking

00:18:04.290 --> 00:18:06.900
of accessibility testing.

00:18:08.430 --> 00:18:09.230
Then we'll begin.

00:18:09.230 --> 00:18:10.730
I hope that was clear for everyone.

00:18:11.820 --> 00:18:17.540
I always begin-- Now, I'm going
to give a few criteria or tests

00:18:17.540 --> 00:18:21.420
that should be implemented
pre-production, that we call them

00:18:21.420 --> 00:18:26.470
the critical mass before you
can even release your product,

00:18:26.470 --> 00:18:29.140
but that maybe you can
do this automatically.

00:18:29.140 --> 00:18:31.280
This is what we're trying to
test at SenseIT, and this is

00:18:31.280 --> 00:18:34.470
what I'm trying to
bring to the world.

00:18:34.470 --> 00:18:39.160
There are critical tests
that should be implemented

00:18:39.160 --> 00:18:41.370
before you release a product.

00:18:41.370 --> 00:18:46.540
We understand that there's a way
that the manual testing techniques

00:18:46.540 --> 00:18:49.080
that we've implemented
for all these years

00:18:49.080 --> 00:18:53.160
might be slowing down
the release cycles.

00:18:53.160 --> 00:18:58.230
Therefore, we're coming out with
ways that we can implement testing

00:18:58.230 --> 00:19:02.610
within development,
offering that heavy lift

00:19:02.610 --> 00:19:06.230
of what a manual tester would
be doing, in order to assure

00:19:06.230 --> 00:19:09.450
that there are no barriers
initially when released.

00:19:09.450 --> 00:19:14.810
Doesn't mean that we don't need
testing post-release, but the issues

00:19:14.810 --> 00:19:20.470
that can be found later on are
not stopping or barriers to use

00:19:20.470 --> 00:19:22.450
for people with disabilities.

00:19:22.450 --> 00:19:24.980
The first one that I start
with is keyboard functionality.

00:19:24.980 --> 00:19:27.540
I love this image because
I feel it explains

00:19:27.540 --> 00:19:32.030
that keyboard functionality is
not only addressing the population

00:19:32.030 --> 00:19:35.460
of people with disabilities,
rather there are people that prefer

00:19:35.460 --> 00:19:38.530
to use keyboard,
there are people or smaller humans

00:19:38.530 --> 00:19:42.390
that have an easier
time using a keyboard.

00:19:42.390 --> 00:19:44.620
Just like when we speak of
the population of people

00:19:44.620 --> 00:19:48.030
with disabilities,
sometimes you can't use the keyboard.

00:19:48.030 --> 00:19:51.390
Sometimes your functions don't allow
you to use-- I'm sorry, a mouse.

00:19:51.390 --> 00:19:54.880
Sometimes your functionality
doesn't allow you to use a mouse

00:19:54.880 --> 00:19:56.930
and therefore,
keyboard functionality has

00:19:56.930 --> 00:19:59.730
to be implemented the same
way that we do a mouse.

00:19:59.730 --> 00:20:02.260
If I go back to square
one, what does that mean?

00:20:02.260 --> 00:20:04.410
When we have a click of a
mouse, we need to make sure

00:20:04.410 --> 00:20:06.500
that it functions
correctly with a keyboard.

00:20:06.500 --> 00:20:12.560
Not only the function of the
actual element, the button,

00:20:12.560 --> 00:20:16.050
where if you need to
press the Submit button

00:20:16.050 --> 00:20:20.930
or click the Submit button,
the Submit button has to be pressable

00:20:20.930 --> 00:20:26.790
by the keyboard, but you also
have to be able to navigate to

00:20:26.790 --> 00:20:28.180
and from the keyboard.

00:20:28.180 --> 00:20:29.350
How do we test for that?

00:20:29.350 --> 00:20:30.550
We have to use the product.

00:20:30.550 --> 00:20:33.660
This is part of what we're
doing with the simulator.

00:20:33.660 --> 00:20:36.936
We're trying to change the behavior

00:20:36.936 --> 00:20:41.480
of existing functional
testing scripts

00:20:41.480 --> 00:20:44.770
to simulate the way
that we would test it

00:20:44.770 --> 00:20:48.860
from a keyboard functionality,
keyboard navigation,

00:20:48.860 --> 00:20:53.430
keyboard Enter perspective,
as part of these success criteria.

00:20:53.430 --> 00:20:54.970
That's number one.

00:20:54.970 --> 00:20:58.280
If we dive a little bit deeper
and we go into this menu,

00:21:01.620 --> 00:21:06.900
then here we have an
example of a dropdown menu.

00:21:06.900 --> 00:21:09.050
We can see that we
have the icons on top.

00:21:09.050 --> 00:21:14.140
I place the focus on
the dropdown menu itself

00:21:14.140 --> 00:21:15.780
so we could see the items.

00:21:15.780 --> 00:21:19.390
In this case, we need to make
sure that we can navigate to

00:21:19.390 --> 00:21:25.640
and from the top menu,
open up the dropdown menu,

00:21:25.640 --> 00:21:28.620
and then we can actually
navigate within the menu

00:21:28.620 --> 00:21:32.050
so that we can reach, let's
say, my nutrition insights.

00:21:32.050 --> 00:21:35.060
By the way, this is the Kroger
website, if anybody just shopped

00:21:35.060 --> 00:21:40.780
at Kroger and recognizes
it, so this is a snippet.

00:21:42.300 --> 00:21:45.100
It's not to come and show
issues, rather it's to just come

00:21:45.100 --> 00:21:49.620
and show what we are looking for when
we speak of keyboard functionality.

00:21:49.620 --> 00:21:53.150
As you know, you have to be able
to go through the entire menu.

00:21:53.150 --> 00:21:58.470
Then, of course, you'll see in
the next few slides, the tests

00:21:58.470 --> 00:22:00.660
that also have to be implemented
not only to make sure

00:22:00.660 --> 00:22:05.190
that the keyboard works,
but that we have focus and whatnot.

00:22:05.190 --> 00:22:09.110
If I take a moment here and
I jump over to my suggestions

00:22:09.110 --> 00:22:14.620
for learning how to test
or understanding what needs

00:22:14.620 --> 00:22:19.190
to be done with assessments,
not only by using a tool,

00:22:19.190 --> 00:22:22.770
and not only by reading the
WCAG, but really trying

00:22:22.770 --> 00:22:26.610
to understand and implement
design as a first step

00:22:26.610 --> 00:22:29.790
within your organization,
we always recommend

00:22:29.790 --> 00:22:36.700
the Accessibility Design Patterns,
the APG that can be found online.

00:22:36.700 --> 00:22:42.610
The W3C created this website where
I really think that it speaks

00:22:42.610 --> 00:22:48.800
to the design and development
teams to really understand

00:22:48.800 --> 00:22:50.130
what needs to be done.

00:22:50.130 --> 00:22:54.020
I still think there's a lot
of information here that may

00:22:54.020 --> 00:22:57.630
or may not be understood
unless someone

00:22:57.630 --> 00:23:01.220
within an organization is
dedicated to accessibility.

00:23:02.350 --> 00:23:06.620
Yet, we still suggest that if you're
looking for keyboard functionality,

00:23:06.620 --> 00:23:10.450
and we have the menu,
the menu bar and buttons,

00:23:10.450 --> 00:23:13.730
then there's ways to really
understand how to implement this

00:23:13.730 --> 00:23:16.310
from the beginning.

00:23:16.310 --> 00:23:19.820
That's why I always
recommend clients,

00:23:19.820 --> 00:23:25.220
whether or not you use our
platform, or you've decided

00:23:25.220 --> 00:23:31.260
to manually test every
process, turning to

00:23:31.260 --> 00:23:35.030
the accessibility design
guidelines will really,

00:23:35.030 --> 00:23:38.990
really give you a leverage and
a kick-start on making sure

00:23:38.990 --> 00:23:41.910
that the rest of your
elements or the components

00:23:41.910 --> 00:23:45.810
that you're building will be
accessible from the design phases.

00:23:47.360 --> 00:23:53.000
The next criteria and
set of criteria and tests

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:55.490
that we speak about are
assistive technologies.

00:23:55.490 --> 00:23:59.870
Of course, keyboard covers the need,
it's also an assistive technology

00:23:59.870 --> 00:24:03.920
from our view,
but here we're talking specifically

00:24:03.920 --> 00:24:08.310
about external technologies such
as the infamous screen reader,

00:24:08.310 --> 00:24:11.330
which behaves in a certain way.

00:24:11.330 --> 00:24:14.520
We need to make sure that
the product is going to-

00:24:14.520 --> 00:24:19.850
the expected behavior out of
elements will also be utilized

00:24:19.850 --> 00:24:24.170
or usable by assistive
technologies.

00:24:24.170 --> 00:24:26.540
Therefore,
we start with name and role.

00:24:26.540 --> 00:24:31.640
If we remember the slide that
I showed with the dropdown menu

00:24:31.640 --> 00:24:37.020
for keyboard functionality,
the icons had the labels under them.

00:24:38.150 --> 00:24:42.680
That, of course, we can see
that I've blacked out the names

00:24:45.800 --> 00:24:49.700
to focus here on
what we are missing.

00:24:49.700 --> 00:24:53.058
Because technically,
if a screen reader is navigating

00:24:53.058 --> 00:24:58.500
through this page, the screen reader
will read out what it can pick up.

00:24:58.500 --> 00:25:05.120
If these icons don't have some sort
of a label or a name implemented,

00:25:05.120 --> 00:25:07.130
then the screen reader is
not going to pick it up.

00:25:07.130 --> 00:25:10.290
What's more,
if I'm not using a screen reader

00:25:10.290 --> 00:25:12.860
and I'm just using this,
and I want something

00:25:12.860 --> 00:25:17.230
that's a little bit more simple
to use and understandable, hence,

00:25:17.230 --> 00:25:22.610
accessible, then having these
icons doesn't necessarily allude

00:25:22.610 --> 00:25:23.850
to what they're doing.

00:25:23.850 --> 00:25:25.230
I have to guess.

00:25:25.230 --> 00:25:32.400
Now, I think part of the reason that
accessibility is not a given has

00:25:32.400 --> 00:25:34.850
to do with the generation
that we're in today,

00:25:34.850 --> 00:25:40.030
where the digital transformation
over the last 20 years has allowed us

00:25:40.030 --> 00:25:44.640
to raise the next generation to
understanding what everything means.

00:25:44.640 --> 00:25:49.420
Three dots means it's a menu,
somebody that looks like a person

00:25:49.420 --> 00:25:51.670
must be your sign-in
or your account.

00:25:51.670 --> 00:25:57.820
If it's a cart, then it must
be where all of my shopping,

00:25:57.820 --> 00:26:01.040
the purchases go for.

00:26:02.800 --> 00:26:04.680
Accessibility doesn't assume.

00:26:04.680 --> 00:26:12.040
We assume that the user
doesn't know and therefore,

00:26:12.040 --> 00:26:13.470
we want to simplify it.

00:26:14.640 --> 00:26:17.540
This is something that
I always allude to.

00:26:17.540 --> 00:26:21.680
Of course, I take everyone back--
Oh, I missed a slide.

00:26:21.680 --> 00:26:26.680
This is another one that I usually
recommend our clients to go back

00:26:26.680 --> 00:26:29.860
and to read a little bit about name
and role and to better understand

00:26:29.860 --> 00:26:33.790
what can be implemented, of course,
with keeping your design in mind.

00:26:35.100 --> 00:26:40.020
If I move on, focus order tends
to be a little bit confusing

00:26:40.020 --> 00:26:43.330
when I speak to people that
don't know accessibility.

00:26:43.330 --> 00:26:46.080
That's primarily because
a lot of people think that

00:26:46.080 --> 00:26:51.270
if I've already clicked on the
sign-in icon or pressed on it

00:26:51.270 --> 00:26:57.510
with my Enter key and the
drop dropdown menu works,

00:26:57.510 --> 00:26:59.560
then we're good to go.

00:26:59.560 --> 00:27:02.740
You want somebody to navigate
through your dropdown menu.

00:27:02.740 --> 00:27:04.620
How are they going to do that?

00:27:04.620 --> 00:27:08.340
It's great that you're tabbing
through, but if the focus is not

00:27:08.340 --> 00:27:11.760
being tabbed through and you
actually have to use your arrow keys,

00:27:12.810 --> 00:27:15.833
then this dropdown
menu is inaccessible,

00:27:15.834 --> 00:27:16.910
and you've actually missed

00:27:16.910 --> 00:27:20.650
the whole point of what you've
done with your keyboard navigation.

00:27:20.650 --> 00:27:26.720
This is another test that we find
it's super critical for a product

00:27:26.720 --> 00:27:30.760
to go through pre-production.

00:27:30.760 --> 00:27:34.240
It's also something that we've
implemented within SenseIT,

00:27:34.240 --> 00:27:38.200
understanding that it's one of the
more critical tests that we used

00:27:38.200 --> 00:27:41.160
to do manually,
and we'd like to see that this is

00:27:41.160 --> 00:27:49.520
just navigating through all elements
on a page and able to focus,

00:27:49.520 --> 00:27:54.580
the keyboard can focus on the
elements that it needs to.

00:27:54.580 --> 00:27:58.410
That was a lot of information,
and I always love to talk about this.

00:27:58.410 --> 00:28:03.250
I try to keep it at the higher
level rather than go technical.

00:28:03.250 --> 00:28:06.440
My background, by the way,
is not of a subject-matter expert.

00:28:06.440 --> 00:28:09.480
I've learned everything that
I've learned through doing

00:28:09.480 --> 00:28:12.800
and through speaking to people and
through reading, and I keep learning.

00:28:12.800 --> 00:28:16.780
If there's anything here that you
feel that I should expand upon

00:28:16.780 --> 00:28:20.560
or that I should add to,
please, by all means, add it

00:28:20.560 --> 00:28:24.690
to the comments or we can
discuss it afterwards.

00:28:24.690 --> 00:28:26.630
I'm happy to take your thoughts.

00:28:27.800 --> 00:28:33.680
Finally, if I spoke all this time
about SenseIT and what I believe

00:28:33.680 --> 00:28:37.883
that combination
between test automation,

00:28:37.883 --> 00:28:40.419
the world of test automation
and accessibility,

00:28:40.419 --> 00:28:42.390
I'll give you a
little bit of a hint

00:28:42.390 --> 00:28:45.370
to where I see the future of
accessibility testing and what it is

00:28:45.370 --> 00:28:48.860
that we're trying to do at SenseIT.

00:28:48.860 --> 00:28:52.440
Which is really to fill
that gap or mind the gap

00:28:52.440 --> 00:28:57.940
between the test automation that's
implemented in organizations

00:28:57.940 --> 00:29:02.360
to test functionality and
performance and security and whatnot,

00:29:02.360 --> 00:29:06.480
and then what we see as kind of
the stepbrother of accessibility.

00:29:07.550 --> 00:29:11.380
We no longer want accessibility
to be left behind at all.

00:29:11.380 --> 00:29:17.820
It has to keep up with the speed
of development, with the world

00:29:17.820 --> 00:29:23.130
of DevOps and the cloud, and
everywhere that technology is going,

00:29:23.130 --> 00:29:27.090
accessibility has to
be implemented within.

00:29:27.090 --> 00:29:31.490
It has to be integrated
into the development cycle,

00:29:31.490 --> 00:29:36.350
and I think it's a huge
part of product development.

00:29:36.350 --> 00:29:40.850
I believe that in the future,
organizations are going to understand

00:29:40.850 --> 00:29:47.170
that accessibility positively affects
usability, and they will be able

00:29:47.170 --> 00:29:50.003
to measure the
positive ROI that comes

00:29:50.004 --> 00:29:52.400
from implementing accessibility.

00:29:52.400 --> 00:29:56.060
However, with that being
said, I don't believe

00:29:56.060 --> 00:29:59.421
that accessibility
can be truly measured

00:29:59.422 --> 00:30:02.900
before it is truly integrated
into development.

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:06.840
In a moment, I'll explain to
you my view of integrating

00:30:06.840 --> 00:30:12.640
into the development cycle,
but when I speak of accessibility

00:30:12.640 --> 00:30:16.840
being integrated,
I mean that on a high level,

00:30:16.840 --> 00:30:20.500
the business stakeholders
understand that accessibility

00:30:20.500 --> 00:30:24.850
is an integral part of their
organization, digital accessibility.

00:30:24.850 --> 00:30:31.450
Because without it, you're not
moving forward, you're not going

00:30:31.450 --> 00:30:36.710
to allow your consumers to
enjoy or to reap the benefits

00:30:36.710 --> 00:30:38.090
of what you're offering.

00:30:38.090 --> 00:30:41.930
Because at the end of the day,
accessibility is a growing market,

00:30:41.930 --> 00:30:46.230
or the population of people with
disabilities is a growing population,

00:30:46.230 --> 00:30:49.480
whether we want to believe it or
not, but that's reality.

00:30:52.080 --> 00:30:56.090
If I come into what we're trying
to do here with SenseIT is

00:30:56.090 --> 00:30:59.220
to really take a traditional
development cycle,

00:30:59.220 --> 00:31:04.780
where you can see this is a
diagram of a high-level process

00:31:04.780 --> 00:31:06.800
of development build.

00:31:06.800 --> 00:31:10.030
I generally have two slides showing
that automatic testing comes

00:31:10.030 --> 00:31:15.400
after build, and then we have manual
accessibility testing before release,

00:31:16.460 --> 00:31:17.440
if at all.

00:31:17.440 --> 00:31:21.860
What I'm showing in this
diagram is that we are combining

00:31:21.860 --> 00:31:25.710
or we're creating a process
where automatic testing

00:31:25.710 --> 00:31:30.250
for accessibility is done
simultaneous to automatic testing

00:31:30.250 --> 00:31:33.100
for mainstream users.

00:31:33.100 --> 00:31:37.370
Therefore, this is allowing
accessibility testing,

00:31:37.370 --> 00:31:40.470
critical accessibility testing
to be implemented pre-release.

00:31:40.470 --> 00:31:44.040
Again, this automatic testing for
accessibility that we're doing

00:31:44.040 --> 00:31:45.850
in SenseIT is a simulator.

00:31:45.850 --> 00:31:49.500
It takes into account keyboard
navigation by interacting

00:31:49.500 --> 00:31:53.790
with the product, which is really
not something that we've seen

00:31:53.790 --> 00:31:55.290
until now.

00:31:56.400 --> 00:31:59.450
It's one of the main reasons
that I believe this can have

00:31:59.450 --> 00:32:02.290
a positive effect on what we're
trying to do in accessibility

00:32:02.290 --> 00:32:10.130
because we won't forego that
interactive element of testing.

00:32:10.130 --> 00:32:12.090
The whole idea is to come
in to change the approach

00:32:12.090 --> 00:32:13.370
to digital accessibility.

00:32:13.370 --> 00:32:17.030
I mentioned it in the beginning,
where we find that organizations

00:32:17.030 --> 00:32:19.080
that are mature enough to
understand that they need

00:32:19.080 --> 00:32:21.610
to implement some sort
of accessibility program

00:32:21.610 --> 00:32:25.220
or standard operating
procedures for accessibility,

00:32:25.220 --> 00:32:31.680
can accept a platform that can
leverage the existing tests

00:32:31.680 --> 00:32:35.430
that they're already doing and
execute them as accessibility tests.

00:32:35.430 --> 00:32:39.890
They can implement or
execute automatic assessments

00:32:39.890 --> 00:32:44.200
by using a simulator that we have
to offer, but also understand

00:32:44.200 --> 00:32:45.700
that it's not the end of the road.

00:32:45.700 --> 00:32:48.300
This is not the be-all and
end-all for accessibility testing,

00:32:48.300 --> 00:32:52.480
rather it's a really great start
for them to release products

00:32:52.480 --> 00:32:57.010
that have limited barriers
or no critical barriers.

00:32:57.010 --> 00:33:01.060
Then, of course, in the way of
technology, we need to make sure

00:33:01.060 --> 00:33:05.960
that companies will adopt such
a tool or such a platform.

00:33:05.960 --> 00:33:10.240
Therefore, we really need to make
sure that accessibility speaks

00:33:10.240 --> 00:33:15.620
to the non-accessibility
professionals or personnel

00:33:15.620 --> 00:33:16.960
within an organization.

00:33:16.960 --> 00:33:21.280
Therefore, it needs to be simply
integrated into existing processes,

00:33:21.280 --> 00:33:27.850
and simply used or the way
it's set up and then used needs

00:33:27.850 --> 00:33:30.929
to be something that
is not too complex

00:33:30.930 --> 00:33:33.470
and doesn't disturb the process.

00:33:34.700 --> 00:33:37.190
This is part of my
research and development.

00:33:37.190 --> 00:33:40.040
Like I said, I believe accessibility
is usability for people

00:33:40.040 --> 00:33:41.180
with disabilities.

